fr.reflexe.viewshell.api.data

Interface IList


  • public interface IList
    Provides access to records provided by a data source obtained from a connector. List instance definitions are immutable; to change the filter, sort, or range, you must create another instance.

    Thread safety: implementations are required to be safe for concurrent read/write access.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    REFLEXE Technologies
    See Also:
    IFetchable.fetchList(ticket,filter,sort,range), IListView.toList(rangeOffset)

      • fetchItems

        List<IItem> fetchItems()
                throws FetchException
        Fetches items from the connector's data source. The user associated with this list may imply rules for data access and workflow, and for filtering visibility. Until this method is invoked, no operational data should be retrieved from the connector.

        Fetching items using this method is an atomic operation, however it is unsuitable for fetching large datasets, as it required buffering of the dataset in memory. For large datasets, consider instead using streams.

        Returns:
        the matching list of items, constrained by the range (if defined). When nothing matches, this returns an empty list, not null.
        Throws:
        FetchException - if item data could not be retrieved.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        stream()

      • stream

        default Stream<IItem> stream()
                      throws FetchException
        Streams items from the connector's data source.

        The default implementation prefetches all items into a buffer and then streams all results from the buffer. Other implementations may be able to optimize streaming to avoid the resource usage overhead implied by the default prefetching implementation.

        Fetching items using this method is not guaranteed to be an atomic operation (results may be truncated when retrieving items from the stream if a failure occurs in an external resource, such as a database or the network).

        Returns:
        a stream, never null.
        Throws:
        FetchException - if initial stream data could not be retrieved. Note that lazily-fetched streams may fail to return all items if a fetch failure occurs after retrieving an arbitrary number of initial stream items.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        fetchItems()

      • getSort

        ISort getSort()
        Gets the sorting rules that apply to this list, if defined. If no rules are defined, then the order of fetched items will depend on the connector, which may lead to unpredictable range queries.
        Returns:
        the sorting (if defined), or null.

      • getRange

        IRange getRange()
        Gets the range that applies to this list, if defined. If there is no range, then the list will contain all records available from the source (or a subset, if a filter is defined).
        Returns:
        the range, if defined, or null.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:

      • next

        IList next()
    throws FetchException
        Gets an immutable list instance referring to the next range. The next range is defined by adding the current range's size to the current range's first index.

        Note: the availability of items in is not verified when invoking this method (it just defines a new range, and may defer actual fetching), therefore car should be taken when invoking this method repeatedly.

        Returns:
        the definition of the list for the next range of items.
        Throws:
        FetchException - if no range is defined.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        getRange()

      • previous

        IList previous()
        throws FetchException
        Gets an immutable list instance referring to the previous range. The previous range is defined by subtracting the current range's size from the current range's first index. When this would result in the first index of the previous range, then the first index is set to zero (without affecting the range size).

        Note: the availability of items in is not verified when invoking this method (it just defines a new range, and may defer actual fetching), therefore car should be taken when invoking this method repeatedly. However, it is not possible to obtain a range with a first index less than or equal to zero; any such attempt will lead to an exception being thrown.

        Returns:
        the definition of the list for the previous range of items.
        Throws:
        FetchException - if no range is defined, or if the first index of the current range is equal to zero.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        getRange()
